beastlordfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=994.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Expect something soon..</span><hr size=1> Expect a big post by Me in a couple days or so, now that I know there's a perm-post for PvPing for BST...<br><br>FYI - I play on TZ &amp; am a lv29 BST(the hardest levels to PK for a bst are pre-SoW).<br><br>~Byooki<br>TZ <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFFF><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub78.ezboard.com/udopievoodooserpent.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Dopie VoodooSerpent</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Growing Claws</span><br>  Posts: 10<br> <font color=#871F78>(4/9/02 5:37:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub115.ezboard.com/feqbeastlordfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=994.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   As promised, here's a sneak peak!</span><hr size=1> As I promised, I would write up a guide for a BST in PvP... while it isn't the finished product but this is what I was able to throw together in about half an hour of just scribbling stuff down..<br><br>Beastlord's In PvP<br><br>SOE designed the Beastlord class to be a hybrid that heavily relies on their pet. Their intentions are generally geared towards PvE situations, and not PvP. Just because a BST almost has to soley rely on their pet to carry their weight in PvE, that does Not have to hold true in PvP. I'm not saying you Can't hide behind your pet when you're out PKing, but it isn't wise. Do Not forget that a BST can Melee, afterall one of our parent classes is the Monk. So we have the ability to fight, if and only if You have kept your melee skills up and maxed(if possible).<br><br>From personal experience, keep All weapon skills maxed even combat-related skills.. <br>A List of Skills To Keep Maxed For PvPing:<br>1hb<br>2hb<br>Piercing<br>Hand to Hand<br>Throwing<br>Bind Wound<br>Swimming<br>Sense Heading<br><br>*I would list Dodge, Riposte, Block, but they naturally go up when you're out XPing.<br>*I would mention skills such as Defense, Offense, etc etc, but like Dodge, Riposte &amp; Block, they naturally        increase when XPing.<br><br>Spell Related Skills:<br>Abjure<br>Alteration<br>Conjuration<br>*Divination<br>Evocation<br>*Channeling<br>Meditate<br><br>* - Indicates Importance.<br><br>*Divination is a key skill involving one spell that not only in PvE, but in PvP as well serves as one of your most valuable spell assets - Flash of Light.<br>*Channeling is important when you need to channel through a Pure Melee or another Hybrid pummeling you while you're trying to get that heal off or that Flash of Light, or DoT, or what ever.<br><br>You might be asking why keep these skills up and you might also not be asking, I'll answer this now..<br><br>I know this little write up won't cover Every possible scenario, because in a PvP situation the battle can sway any way at any given moment. And when the battle suddenly shifts, its when having all these skills up to an average level will help turn the tides of the fight in your favor.<br><br>A specific reason to keep to keep Melee Skills up is a simple reason. If you're able to use a vast variety of different weapon combinations, you will be able to deal damage in ways not seen by your opponant. <br><br>EX: You get jumped by some Paladin or SK or Ranger, they see you with your 2hb and figure a jousting match, since you don't have double attack and they do, you're screwed in this fight. Not necessarily, if you have 1hb up and h2h up and piercing, well each of those weapon skills gives you access to a bunch of different weapons.. if you know PvP and you know weapons, you know Iam talking about Procs. I love being jumped by a hybrid thinking jousting only to be shocked when I land a Bloodclaw proc on them, they cant get a snare or root off and cant joust me and I'm in their face piercing, crushing &amp; punching in the upwards of 20-40 damage.<br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp This brings me to my next point, Procs aren't the only reason to keep weapon skills up, by being able to switch between a 2hander(slow but big hits - a favorite concept in PvP*jousting*drive-bys*) and no double attack, and being able to move to a quick piercer to get tons of hits in between a hybrid, priest or caster casting to interrupt spells, or being able to go to a 1hb or piercer or hand to hand so that the hybrid or pure melee with SoW, no SoW or whatever, who figures it's going to be a jousting match, they can't joust if you don't joust back.<br><br>Keypoints: Do NOT let the opponant control the fight, if they want to joust but you don't, chase them as they do a drive by hit, if they expect you to joust back then they will most likely stop which means free hits for you <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  don't be afraid to do some circle/straffe fighting with a pure melee. Just because they're a pure melee and you're not doesn't mean they will be superior to you in a circle fight or a glitch walk fight. And if they still try to joust you, that's where you're throwing skill comes into play.. wait for them to run at you and just straffe off to the side, face them and throw a couple shurikens --- it's low dmg, but at least it's damage and they didn't hit you..<br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Remember, how can a Warrior, Rogue or Monk kill you if they can't hit you? If you want to joust but they don't want to, this will quickly become a glitch walk/hill bug fight. This type of PvP encounter is where your pet becomes invaluable. If you're a good hillbugger/glitch walker, they won't hit you or rarely will, your pet's procs will be pounding down their HP while they're focusing on you, you're pet is getting some excellant back shots(if ONLY they could BS!)<br><br>I guess my thoughts aren't well aimed so, I might as well get into the aspects and roles of our Warders in PvP...<br><br>You will almost Never have someone strictly focus on killing your Warder, then You. Use this to your advantage. While you're jousting, hillbugging, tunnel fighting, glitch walking, straff/circling or whatever. The majority of all PvPers will focus on the master and ignore the pet.. big mistake against a BST 'cuz our pet's Proc. I know for a fact that the lv22 pet imbue proc, Spirit of the Blizzard, is 41 dmg. Now that's a harder hit than ANY other pet(except charmed) around that level. <br><br>In most fights, your pet will mostly get in the way and annoy you and most importantly your opponant, by annoying them personally, they will lose concentration(its not just a physical game, its mental endurance). But mostly your pet will only add additional damage. <br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>My Main use of my pet is when I run into that slick hill-bugger. A little thing to note &amp; remember, You Can NOT Hill-Bug a NPC - which is What the BST warder is. If someone is skilled at hill-bugging, sick your pet, and hang back a little bit behind your pet, wait for your Warder to stop and start biting and procing(usually only a couple rounds or so of your pet hitting before they run again).. this is why you stay somewhat close to your pet, 'cuz as Soon as it stops, run RIGHT TO your pet and as you get to the front of your pet, just hit your Auto-Attack Hotkey (whatever it may be, default is the 'A' key).<br><br>A Hill-Bugger has a general assumption that if he's hill-bugging, so are you. When you run up on them, as they're thinking how sly they are, you hit them and run past them and the process starts again.. a good thing to do is switch over to a 3rd Person Camera Angle, so you can watch your pet start moving as you pass your target.<br><br>Another thing that is great, is when you're hill-bugging, you just stop, watch your pet approach in 3rd person and as they run past, hit your Auto-Attack and free hits, yay <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  and while you're hill-bugging, or your pet is tracking for you, the warder is getting Tons of free hits &amp; procs(and they add up and hurt).<br><br>Another tactic, is glitch walking, you can't glitch-walk NPCs. Tag your pet on a walker and watch the hits fly and just sit back and DoT em, or try and get some hits in.<br><br>Circling &amp; Straffing - A combination of circling quickly about, or in lazy-8's or running straight, then stopping and moving suddenly to the side.. or what have you.. Just like hill-bugging &amp; glitch walking, you can not ditch a pet without having a Running/Walking Speed Enhancer (SoW, Jboots, AA Ability). If the person is doing this to you, just run straight, eventually they'll catch on after only their pet is hitting them and they aren't hitting anything but air. At this point, you can readjust your surrounding to improve your abilities to circle/straffe, or you can joust them as they come to you, or you can glitch walk, or hill-bug, or run, the possibilities just go on and on on what you may do at that point.<br><br>When you can break away from conflict and be able to readjust yourself to the point of improving your ability to fight with a higher proficiency, more power to you and the greater the chance to succeed in winning this ballot.<br><br>Another thing people LOVE to do with our pets is agro them and run away to rid the world of our warder... wait until they are a good distance off with your pet, then just cancel the icon, summon a new one and buff its level &amp; proc.. they hate it when they come back thinking, 'Just that dumb BST to kill now!' and you have a whole new pet buffed &amp; proc'd waiting for them smiling <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br><br>That's all I have at the moment, I am however intending to add about 1-2 Class-Specific encounter per night until I have all the bases covered.<br><br>Until then, feel free to read it over and critique it.. Please post any suggestions, concerns or topics you'd like me to cover or if you have differing opinions and what not <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br><br>~Byooki <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFFF><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub78.ezboard.com/uautarchvz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Autarch VZ</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://pages.prodigy.net/amblint/Images/lilflag.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Beast Prince</span><br>  Posts: 63<br> <font color=#871F78>(4/10/02 10:04:55 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub115.ezboard.com/feqbeastlordfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=994.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://pages.prodigy.net/amblint/Images/DEQC.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: As promised, here's a sneak peak!</span><hr size=1> Just a little stupid newbie question here. What is hill-bugging and glitch-walking?<br><br> <p><center><img src="http://pages.prodigy.net/amblint/sslashu.gif" border=0></center><BR></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFFF><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub78.ezboard.com/udopievoodooserpent.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Dopie VoodooSerpent</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Sniff! Sniff!</span><br>  Posts: 11<br> <font color=#871F78>(4/10/02 5:28:16 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub115.ezboard.com/feqbeastlordfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=994.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   .. response to hill-bugging/g-walking...*supplement</span><hr size=1> Not a n00b question at all.. I figured I'd get Someone who'd ask what those 2 terms meant.. I'll try my best to explain them in words, and in the final document, i'll refine the description...<br><br>Hill-Bugging:<br><br>The title is pretty self explanatory if you know what H-bugging is. Hill-Bugging, simply put(or as simple as I can put it), there's some graphic glitches, notice sometimes when a mob is running up/down/along a hill,dune, some incline and it just disappears or looks like it keep walking, but when you chase to hit it you get the ..''Too far away&quot; message? That's a simple example and explanation..<br><br>What happens when you hill-bug.. You're running up/down/along an incline(hill or dune, etc etc) and as you, just suddenly STOP, don't turn, don't move.. but what appears on other's screens is Your character keeps on moving in the direction you would have kept going in if you had kept running.<br><br>This is vital in PvP, cuz when someone's chasing you they base their chase on what they see.. when they see you running, they keep chasing but if you stop they pass you and gives you the offensive or chance to run some more in a different direction than the path your pursuer took making more distance, etc etc..<br><br>Glitch Walking...<br><br>This one has several definitions. Most namely include a combination of running, walking, straffing and circling in a consistant direction.. This method is mostly used when you're snared and are trying to escape the person pounding on your back.. a good g-walker can make it from the WC zoneline in EC to the NRO zoneline snared and not die.. im not That good at it and I did that. This tactic is also used by peeps in a fungi/ikky bp cuz it reduces your dmg intake and thus helping their regen..<br><br>I know those explanations seem vague(to me they do).. but once I finish my final product, the explanations will be more complete and detailed.. <br><br>Thanx for adressing the terminology tho <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br><br>~Byooki <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFFF><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub78.ezboard.com/uautarchvz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Autarch VZ</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://pages.prodigy.net/amblint/Images/lilflag.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Beast Prince</span><br>  Posts: 72<br> <font color=#871F78>(4/11/02 12:58:41 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub115.ezboard.com/feqbeastlordfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=994.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://pages.prodigy.net/amblint/Images/DEQC.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: .. response to hill-bugging/g-walking...*supplement</span><hr size=1> Thanks for the description. I'll have to work on those things and see how it works out.<br> <p><center><img src="http://pages.prodigy.net/amblint/sslashu.gif" border=0></center><BR></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFFF><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub78.ezboard.com/udopievoodooserpent.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Dopie VoodooSerpent</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Beast in Training</span><br>  Posts: 12<br> <font color=#871F78>(4/11/02 3:08:29 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub115.ezboard.com/feqbeastlordfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=994.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   .. One more thing before I get back to the final document</span><hr size=1> ... Glad my words could have provided some sort of abstract description of those 2 techniques.. You will almost Never see someone who plays on a bluebe(non PvP server) server use those 